{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492881"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1175"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1175"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.15,0.26,0.43,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16820"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1784"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42236"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents with a two day history of fever, sore throat, runny nose, cough and headache. She has now noticed a rash on her face spreading to the trunk (image) and limbs  accompanied with mild joint pain. On examination there is a diffuse erythematous maculopapular rash on her body, which is blanching in nature. No vesicles or bullae are present, her oral mucosa appears normal and her cervical lymph nodes are palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chicken pox","Pityriasis rosea","Scarlet fever","Rubella","Rickettsial infection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe case of an adult woman with fever, blanching rash lymphadenopathy and mild joint pain are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Erubella, \u003C/strong\u003Ean infection caused by the rubella virus. Rubella virus is transmitted from person to person via aerosolised particles from the respiratory tract. It presents with fever, sore throat, a rash starting from face and extending to the trunk, and  associated with fatigue. Joint pain is a common symptom in adults, particularly women. The disease is usually mild and self-limiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERubella infection during pregnancy causes congenital rubella syndrome, including the classic triad of cataracts, cardiac abnormalities and sensorineural deafness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChickenpox\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as\u003Cem\u003E varicella\u003C/em\u003E, is a highly contagious disease caused by the initial infection with varicella zoster virus (VZV). It starts with a characteristic skin rash that forms small, itchy blisters, which eventually scab over starting on the chest, back, and face spreading to the rest of the body. Other symptoms include fever, feeling of tiredness, headache and stomachache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E is an infectious disease caused by group A streptococcus, characterised by exudative pharyngitis, high grade fever, and bright red rash that covers most of the body. It appears as a diffuse redness of the skin with small papules, that give the characteristic sandpaper texture to the rash The tongue initially has a white coating on it, while the papillae of the tongue are swollen and reddened. The protrusion of the red papillae through the white coating gives the tongue a \u0022white strawberry\u0022 appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERickettsial infection \u003C/strong\u003Eis caused due to a group of bacteria that are transmitted to human beings through bite of mites, ticks, lice or fleas. Rickettsia may present as conditions such as rocky mountain spotted fever (RMSF), rickettsial pox, Queensland tick typhus and murine typhus. Symptoms include a rash and joint pain, vomiting, a sudden high fever, chills, headache, abdominal pain and muscle aches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea \u003C/strong\u003Emanifests as an acute, self-limiting, papulosquamous eruption with a duration of 6-8 weeks. The rash often begins as an oval spot on the face, chest, abdomen or back called as herald patch. It is pruritic and can cause fatigue, headache, fever, loss of appetite. In addition to typical papules and scales, forms appearing as very large plaques, hives, vesicles, large blisters, patches, oral lesions, and various other appearances have been noted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rubella is a viral illness characterized by fever, sore throat, a maculopapular rash starting from face and extending to the trunk, and fatigue.","It is a self-limiting condition and usually lasts for 3-4 days"],"references":["ambert N, Strebel P, OrensteinW, Icenogle J, Poland GA. Rubella. Lancet. (2015) 385:2297\u2013307. 10.1016/S0140-6736(14)60539-0.","Dontigny L, Arsenault MY, Martel MJ, et al. Rubella in pregnancy. J Obstet Gynaecol Can. 2008 Feb. 30(2):152-68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16820"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1175"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18582"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18582"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f2741f80-461a-4e25-a1f0-692d95dcaf2f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f2741f80-461a-4e25-a1f0-692d95dcaf2f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":441,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16820"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-18T08:21:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T19:15:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30924"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1063"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":